How an LLM Actually Works — The Big Picture
At its core, a language model does one simple thing:

Given some text, predict what word (token) comes next.

That's it. Do that billions of times on massive amounts of text, and you get something that "understands" language. Here's the journey from zero to a working model:

Stage 1 — Tokenization
Before the model sees any text, words get broken into tokens (chunks). "Hello world" might become ["Hello", " world"] or even ["He", "llo", " wor", "ld"]. Each token gets a number ID.
Stage 2 — Embeddings
Those number IDs get turned into vectors — lists of floating point numbers that capture meaning. Words with similar meanings end up with similar vectors. This is how the model "understands" that "cat" and "kitten" are related.
Stage 3 — The Transformer (the magic part)
This is the core architecture behind Claude, GPT, and nearly every modern LLM. It uses a mechanism called attention — which lets the model look at all words in a sentence simultaneously and figure out which ones are relevant to each other.
Stage 4 — Training
The model reads enormous amounts of text and adjusts its internal numbers (weights) to get better and better at predicting the next token. This is done with an algorithm called backpropagation.
Stage 5 — Inference
Once trained, you feed it a prompt and it predicts one token at a time — that's the text you see streaming out.

