VvisualizeVvisualize show_widgetThe key mental model: the loss is one number. Every weight in the network influenced that number. Backprop asks "if I increase this weight by a tiny amount, does the loss go up or down?" — and computes that answer for every weight simultaneously using the chain rule.

The chain rule in plain English
Say your model is just three operations in sequence:
x → [multiply by W] → [apply ReLU] → [compute loss]
To find how W affects the loss:
∂Loss/∂W = (∂Loss/∂ReLU_output) × (∂ReLU/∂W_output) × (∂W_output/∂W)
Each layer computes its own little local derivative, then multiplies it by whatever gradient is flowing in from the right. That's it. The whole of backprop is just this chain, applied to thousands of weights at once.

The code
We'll build a Value class — a number that remembers how it was created so it can compute its own gradient. This is exactly how PyTorch's autograd works under the hood.
